\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The County shall assign value and sensitivity to information so that security controls are applied consistently and proportionally to the risk of unauthorized access,
 disclosure,
 modification,
 destruction,
 or loss of availability.
 All data residing on County infrastructure or processed on behalf of the County is County property.
 In any conflict between requirements established in this policy and upstream authorities,
 the order of precedence established in the Manual Executive Summary governs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
6.1 Data Classification Schema
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The IT Director shall maintain the County Data Classification Schema.
 The County shall classify all data into one (1) of four (4) levels based on the potential impact of unauthorized disclosure,
 modification,
 destruction,
 or loss of availability.
 Classification shall drive mandatory safeguards,
 handling restrictions,
 and access enforcement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Default Classification
\series default
:
 All County Personnel shall handle data not yet classified as Restricted until the responsible Department Head formally evaluates and assigns a classification level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Prohibited Storage
\series default
:
 All County Personnel shall store and process County data only in repositories and systems approved by the IT Director.
 The use of personal cloud storage,
 personal email accounts,
 unsanctioned collaboration tools,
 or other unauthorized systems to store or process County data is prohibited.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
6.2 Level 1 — Public
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Public information is data explicitly approved for unrestricted distribution.
 Unauthorized disclosure presents no identified risk of harm to the County.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Examples
\series default
:
 Published press releases,
 public meeting agendas,
 job postings,
 public website content.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Minimum Safeguards
\series default
:
 The IT Director shall ensure integrity controls sufficient to prevent unauthorized modification or defacement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
6.3 Level 2 — Internal Use
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Internal Use information is operational data intended for internal County business use.
 Disclosure may cause operational confusion,
 reputational harm,
 or unnecessary disruption but is not inherently sensitive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Examples
\series default
:
 Internal memos,
 internal directories,
 standard procedures,
 non-sensitive drafts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Minimum Safeguards
\series default
:
 All Information Operations Personnel shall enforce standard access controls (unique user authentication),
 standard backup,
 and retention per approved schedules.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
6.4 Level 3 — Confidential
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Confidential information is sensitive data that,
 if compromised,
 could negatively impact individual privacy,
 County finances,
 legal posture,
 or operational security.
 Department Heads shall limit access to personnel with a validated business need-to-know.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Examples
\series default
:
 Personally Identifiable Information (PII) as defined in NRS 603A,
 personnel records,
 vendor contracts containing non-public financial terms,
 draft budgets,
 privileged legal communications.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Minimum Safeguards
\series default
:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
